post_cb({"23454557": {"CommentCount": "3", "ViewCount": "183", "CreationDate": "2014-05-04T09:20:10.830", "LastActivityDate": "2014-05-04T09:49:34.950", "Title": "Is int implicitly signed (C++)?", "AcceptedAnswerId": "23454711", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "23454557", "Score": "0", "Body": "<p>In C++, when I say <code>int i = 0;</code> </p>\n<p>is the int now automatically <code>signed int i = 0;</code> or <code>unsigned int i = 0;</code>?</p>\n<p>I haven't found an answer through Google</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><int><unsigned><signed>", "OwnerUserId": "2713857", "AnswerCount": "3"}, "23454711": {"ParentId": "23454557", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>The C++11 standard (<a href=\"http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/papers/2012/n3337.pdf\">draft</a>) \u00a73.9.1.2 has this to say;</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_23454557_23454711_0\">There are \ufb01ve standard signed integer types : \u201csigned char\u201d, \u201cshort int\u201d, <strong>\u201cint\u201d</strong>, \u201clong int\u201d, and \u201clong long int\u201d.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The C11 standard (<a href=\"http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg14/www/docs/n1570.pdf\">draft</a>) \u00a76.2.5.4 has this to say;</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_23454557_23454711_1\">There are \ufb01ve standard signed integer types, designated as signed char, short int, <strong>int</strong>, long int, and long long int</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It would seem they're both in agreement that <strong>int</strong> is a signed type.</p>\n<p>(<a href=\"http://port70.net/~nsz/c/c89/c89-draft.html#3.1.2.5\">C89</a> \u00a73.1.2.5 also agrees, so it would seem to have been that way as far as I can go back)</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "477878", "LastEditorUserId": "477878", "LastEditDate": "2014-05-04T09:44:35.627", "Id": "23454711", "Score": "9", "CreationDate": "2014-05-04T09:38:59.220", "LastActivityDate": "2014-05-04T09:44:35.627"}, "23454569": {"ParentId": "23454557", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<p>it is signed int by default in c++</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "3540127", "LastEditorUserId": "3540127", "LastEditDate": "2014-05-04T09:49:34.950", "Id": "23454569", "Score": "-2", "CreationDate": "2014-05-04T09:21:24.403", "LastActivityDate": "2014-05-04T09:49:34.950"}, "23454585": {"ParentId": "23454557", "CommentCount": "10", "Body": "<p>Its's signed. You can prove that to yourself by decrementing the integer and seeing that negative values are provided, rather than it wrapping back round to the maximum number for an unsigned integer.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "927168", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "23454585", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2014-05-04T09:23:27.063", "LastActivityDate": "2014-05-04T09:23:27.063"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_23454557_23454711_1": {"section_id": 7211, "quality": 0.875, "length": 14}, "so_23454557_23454711_0": {"section_id": 7211, "quality": 0.9333333333333333, "length": 14}}, "n3337": {"so_23454557_23454711_1": {"section_id": 6955, "quality": 0.875, "length": 14}, "so_23454557_23454711_0": {"section_id": 6955, "quality": 0.9333333333333333, "length": 14}}, "n4659": {"so_23454557_23454711_1": {"section_id": 8720, "quality": 0.8125, "length": 13}, "so_23454557_23454711_0": {"section_id": 8720, "quality": 0.8666666666666667, "length": 13}}}});